@node "OwnIcon" "OwnIcon"
 It`s allowed naturally, to paint your own icons and include it into the
packet. The existing icons you must not delete, but you can rename it
alternatively with new suffixes,

p.e.:  Archive.@{fg highlight}image@{fg text}  -->  Archive.@{fg highlight}original@{fg text} !!

Your own icons have to replace the old names, because the BootMonitor
searching for these, and if it find no icons, it shows no icons. Furthermore,
the icon-files have to be in the root dir, otherwise BootMon does`nt find
them, except you start it from CLI.


@{fg highlight}>>>>> Warning <<<<<, Icons, which was not found, waste also memory.@{fg text}


To safety, BootMon displays below every icon a text, that is fixed, that the
user can control BootMon without icons, too.

Here are the doc for creating your own icons:

You open a paint-program and paint your pics. The size of the icons must not
greater than:

        Width  = 60  pixel in HighRes
        Height = 18  columns in HighRes
        Planes = 3   (8 colours)

otherwise the icons can be displayed wrong.

Now you can start an IFF-converting tool, which can save RAW, too. You can
take the ImageMaker, for instance. You must`nt save a ColorMap and requests
for offsets you must enter with 0. The graphics should be 300 byte great.

Should be an icon too long, p.e. 20 columns in height, then the BootMon cut
the graphic at the 18th column.

Now you rename the original icon with a new suffix. In the CLI you can type,
for instance:

        rename df0:Archive.image to df0:Archive.original

Now you can save your own icon with the original name, for instance
Archive.image, starting the BootMon and now you can see your new
Archive-gadget.
@endnode

@node "Allgemein" "Allgemein"
 To the BootMonitor itself:

The BootMonitor was written in 100% Assembler and should have no bugs (but
thats no warranty). The author takes on no liability for destroyed bootblocks
or discs with that program. In version 1.0 BootMon only reads bootblocks from
discs, that supported trackdisk.device. it supported the  the devices from 0
to 3, for instance the floppies from DF0: to DF3:. Owners of Kickstart 1.3 or
least, have to search for a ASL.library for their Kickstart. Owner of
Kickstart 2.0 and above should have no problems with an ASL.library and
BootMonitor. You can control the program with gadgets or keys, except you are
in the editing mode, where you can use only the keyboard.
@endnode

