@node "GEnd" "GEnd"
 HotKey 'X'

quits the Bootmonitor without requests. Warning, editing bootblocks, which was
unmodified in the @{"Undo" link "Undo" 0}-buffer and was modified, are lost, therefore a little
tip: before editing bootblocks, ever create a copy with `@{"Arch.ĀBB" link "Archive" 0}`. You can
quit the BootMon with CloseGadget, too.
@endnode

@node "Read" "Read"
 HotKey `R`

Means Read BootBlock and read a bootblock from Disc into the memory. The
Undo-buffer don`t used and you can restoring overwitten bootblocks, which are
situated in the Undo-buffer. If it`s not succesfully, BootMon requests an
error message.
@endnode

@node "Write" "Write"
 HotKey `W`

Means Write BootBlock and write back a bootblock onto a disc, but not into the
Undo-buffer. Warning, a bootblock on disc are overwritten If it`s not
successfully, BootMon request an error message, too. `Write BB` has the
feature, that the function calculate the correct checksum of the bootblock,
before it was written. It`s a help, if you have self-written bootblocks and
you don`t know, how you can install them. A description of the structure of a
bootblock is following in this doc.
@endnode

@node "Archive" "Archive"
 HotKey `A`

Means Archive BootBlock and shows a filerequester for the path and the
filename, where the bootblock in memory should to be saved as file. These
files have no fixed format and contain only the dates of the bootblock. Such a
file has exactly a size of 1024 bytes or 1 Kbyte.
@endnode

@node "UnArchive" "UnArchive"
 HotKey `U`

Means UnArchive BootBlock and shows a filerequester, too. Works similar to
@{"Archive" link "Archive" 0}, but in an opposite way, no block are written but a file are reading
(The @{"Undo" link "Undo" 0}-buffer is`nt in use by that.)
@endnode

@node "Laufwerk" "Laufwerk"
 HotKey `L`

try to change the drive, p.e. from DF0: to DF1:. The number of drive are
increased by 1. Is the drive DF3:, the next drive is DF0:. If an error occurs,
an error message appears. In this routine @{fg highlight}NO@{fg text} write or read action on the drive
happens.
@endnode

@node "Execute" "Execute"
 HotKey `T`

Execute a bootblock from memory. The difference to the boot from disc is,
that

1. you can directly start the bootblock from Workbench.

2. the checksum of the bootblock are ignored, that you can start
   bootblocks with destroyed or faulty checksums.

The dates for the bootblock are written, as far as i know, the exec-base in
register A6 and the IORequest in register A1. Should everybody knows another
requesters on the boot action from disc, so he should @{"contact" link "Adresse" 0} me. You can`t
start a not valid bootblock, because before the bootblock starts, the program
checks the first longword. This is a little safety-check of BootMon. The `T`
in the Hotkey means (T)race.
@endnode

@node "Edit" "Edit"
 HotKey `E`

Starts with editing the bootblock on the first byte. BootMon is now in the
editing mode, and the control is limited. You can move the cursor with
following keys:

  <CTRL A>    --- moves the cursor left
  <CTRL S>    --- moves the cursor right
  <CTRL W>    --- moves the cursor up
  <CTRL Y>    --- moves the cursor down
  <CTRL Z>    --- moves the cursor down
  <ENTER>     --- quits the editing mode

The CTRL means the Control-Key, and the other key you have to pressed on @{fg highlight}the
same time@{fg text}, to move the cursor. Every other key is modifying the bootblock. If
you try to exit the main window, you only quit the editing mode. One feature
of the editing mode is, to save the bootblock into the @{"Undo" link "Undo" 0}-buffer on start of
this mode. Now the Undo-buffer is`nt free. Look at the @{"INFO" link "Info" 0}-gadget. Another
feature is opening a @{"secondĀsmallĀwindow" link "CalcWin" 0}, which shows, that BootMon is in
editing mode and shows any helpfully features.

Every edit action is displayed in @{fg highlight}white@{fg text}. A crossing over this characters makes
them black again. In the editing mode no Del- or Backspace key are there, then
you can set back the cursor with the control functions and make the changes
again. The disadvantage is the occupation of the keys Ctrl_A, Ctrl_S, Ctrl_W,
Ctrl_Y, Ctrl_Z and Enter. The purpose is, that A600 User can edit, too. The
A600 has @{fg highlight}NO numeric controlpad@{fg text}.
@endnode

@node "CalcWin" "CalcWin"
 These window accepts @{fg highlight}NO@{fg text} input, and shows only informations.

The meaning of:
     Bytewert:       Is the header.
      Hex:           Output in Hex-Code.

      Dez:           output in decimal scalars.

     Position:       Is the second header.
      Hex:           Output of the address from the cursor in Hex-Code.

      Dez:           Output of the address from the cursor in decimal
                     scalars.

To editing please activate the main window of BootMon, but you can take the
calculator window in the background.
@endnode

@node "Undo" "Undo"
 HotKey `N` Means the N in the word U(n)do, because the key U is already
reserved (UnArchive). With Undo-BootBlock you can cancel the @{fg highlight}last@{fg text}, but only
the last, action on editing. The editing bootblock will be entirely
overwritten with that in memory.
@endnode

@node "Show" "Show"
 HotKey `S`

Means the S in the word (S)how. With that function you can look at the
actually bootblock, and not on that at the @{"Undo" link "Undo" 0}-buffer, because error messages
and other actions use the same output window.
@endnode

@node "Clear" "Clear"
 HotKey `C`

Means the C in the word (C)lear. With that function the actually bootblock in
memory will be delete. The deleted bootblock will be shown now. The
@{"Undo" link "Undo" 0}-buffer don`t be used by these action. But carefully, a write back of such
a bootblock, can make the disc to @{fg highlight}NONDOS@{fg text}. But you can install these disc or
change back the bootblock, generally in that way:

You start the editing mode and write to position 0 as @{fg highlight}capitals@{fg text} `@{bg fill}DOS@{bg back}` and press
the enter-key.

After that you write back the bootblock with `Write BB` to disc.

Another way is, that you make @{fg highlight}INSTANTLY@{fg text} the function `@{"UndoĀBB" link "Undo" 0}` and write the
bootblock again.

The next way are:

You choose the function `@{"UnArchĀBB" link "UnArchive" 0}`, read a bootblock from disc or where you
want, and write it to disc.
@endnode

@node "Info" "Info"
 HotKey `I`

Means (I)nformation about the drive. These function is a help after changing
the drive. It shows the device name, normally `trackdisk.device` and the drive
number, p.e.:

drive number 1 means df1: drive number 0 means df0:

Whether the drive exists or a disc is inserted or not (will showing valid or
not valid).

The status of the Undo-buffer is showing, too (an empty means, that no
@{"Undo" link "Undo" 0}-function can be choosing and is a safety-function for overwriting a
bootblock in the memory.) Warning: Only one start of the @{"Edit" link "Edit" 0}or installs the
@{"Undo" link "Undo" 0}-buffer.
@endnode

@node "Vektor" "Vektor"
 HotKey `V`

Means the (V)ectordisplay. These function is a small safety against viruses.
The most viruses change on start (like p.e. with `@{"Execute" link "Execute" 0}`) the captures. If
one of these vectors has a value other than 0, it will be showing in hex-code
and white. Now all mediums can be threatening, and you should be carefully.
The BootMon doesn`t change vectors. Only unknown bootblocks can that, and the
author gives no warranty or liability for damages on discs or other mediums.
You should use a viruskiller, like p.e. VirusZ from Georg H÷rmann or similar
things.
@endnode

@node "Reset" "Reset"
 HotKey `O`

Means (O)ld or new. These function resets only the actually device, and not
the Program or the Amiga. The device command CMD_RESET is executing.
@endnode

@node "FPrint" "FPrint"
 HotKey `F`

Means (F)ile-Print. These function write an ASCII-Dump of the bootblock into a
file. An ASL-Requester appears for path and filename, where you want to write
the dump. Otherwise the function is similar to @{"Print" link "Print" 0}.
@endnode

@node "FDump" "FDump"
 HotKey `H`

Means (H)ex-Dump into a file. An ASL-Requester appears for the path and
filename, where you want write the dump. These function writes a whole
hex-dump of the bootblock into a file.

Otherwise these function is similar to @{"Dump" link "Dump" 0}.
@endnode

@node "Print" "Print"
 HotKey `P` means (P)rint ASCII to printer. These function write a ASCII-Dump
of the bootblock to the printer. The difference to @{"FPrint" link "FPrint" 0} is, that no
Asl-Requester appears, but the output goes directly to the device PRT:.

The ASCII-Dump consists

OFFSET : ------- 65 ASCII-Characters -------

0000 : DOS.I^³«­-..®r│Š..│.5...dos.library....

The ASCII-Dump contains only printable characters, and bytes lower than $20,
will be replaced with `.`. The purpose of that is, that there are printer
control characters, which can change the printer action.

Warning, if you have no printer or the printer is offline !! In that case
BootMon write the file to the printer and no happens and the file don`t close.
@endnode

@node "Dump" "Dump"
 HotKey `D` Means Print Dump. This is an interesting kind of printing from
bootblocks. The dump shows in that way:

OFFSET : 20 bytes as Hex-Characters 20 Characters as ASCII-Dump

0000: 44 4F 53 00 34 20 43 21 00 00 03 70 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00
DOS.4C!...p.......

On the printer is that a whole row, if the printer can print 90 Characters
into a row.

Warning, if you have no printer or the printer is offline !! In that case
BootMon writes the file to the device, but nothing happens and the file don`t
close.
@endnode

@node "Device" "Device"
 Hotkey `M`

Let you change the device. The filerequester shows DEVS:. So you can choose a
strange device, p.e. ones for MS-DOS Discs. But only the first 512 bytes of
the first and the second Sector are reading. That means, if the RigidDiscBlock
at a harddisk has a size of 1024 at the first block, and no second bootsector
exists, then the first 512 bytes of the RDB and the first 512 bytes at the
second block are the bootblock. Warning, no ROM devices are shown in the
filerequester, you can enter them by input their names followed by a .device,
p.e. scsi.device. You can insert trackdisk.device, too. The @{"Undo-buffer" link "Undo" 0} are
not supported by this function, that you can write these bootblocks to every
medium.

These function use the ASL.library, too, and is only by it`s existing usable.
In the case, that you have no ASL.library, a small info-message appears.
@endnode

@node "Konvert_Boot" "Konvert_Boot"
 Hotkey 'K'

This function do you reaching over the menu `Tools` and it generates an
autonome file, which can run @{fg highlight}without@{fg text} Bootmonitor. This item opens an
ASL-filerequester after converting, therefore this item is locked, if you
don`t have the ASL-library. Now you can type the name of the executable
program into this requester, choosing the right path and makes OK. This file
contains the bootblock as program without `DOS`-code and checksum. You don`t
need these parts of the bootblock. This function proves, whether the code
creates no crashes. If you can exceute a bootblock with @{"Execute" link "Execute" 0}, then you can
convert it into an executable program.

@{fg highlight}The author takes on no liability for damages, viruses or similar evilnesses,
which you can (easier) spread with Bootmonitor. If you violate any Copyrights,
the author takes on no liabilty, too. In this packet no bootblocks including.@{fg text}

This item is thinking for coders, they want to write own trackloaders,
viruskillers or any other useful bootblocks and spread them.
@endnode

@node "Konvert_File" "Konvert_File"
 Hotkey `Q`

I have found no other charakter for this item and you can reach this item over
gadget`s, too. Now to the item Konv. Dat: This item converts executable
programs into bootblocks, but there are several rules:

The programm must contain not more than one hunk.

The program have to be written PC-relative, that means it have to be movable
freely at the memory.

It have to be contain a code-hunk.

The code-hunk must not be greater than 1012 bytes.

What`s that, 1012 bytes ? The bootblock just is 1024 bytes long.

The answer you find in `@{"structureĀofĀaĀbootblock" link "Bootblock" 0}`, where also described, that
the first 12 bytes of the bootblock are reserved for the operating system and
you didn`t shall change them.

This item searches now for a code-hunk and proves its length. Is the hunk too
long, a error message appears and the file isn`t converted. Warning, Bootmon
doesn`t check for converting tables. Such programs will be converted, whether
it runs or not.

How you can write programs into one only hunk:

Totally easy:

On most assemblers, p.e. Maxon-Ass, you can find the pseudo-functions
`SECTION` or similar. These functions `sections` the code into small parts to
make easier the loading and creating of such programs. In fact, such files,
which consists at several hunks, will be move to the memory as many sections
and not as one part. So you can copy dates to chip-ram without allocating
memory before. The disadvantage of this method is the creating of converting
tables for the routine LoadSegment() from the Dos-library. With that tables
the code will be converted and there is an executable program for Amiga-DOS.
But this table (HUNK_RELOC) makes the file longer. Now you can understood, why
you don`t should use files with more than one section for converting. The part
of memory, where the bootblock is loading, isn`t fixed forever. My opinion is,
that the bootblock ever will be loading into the chip-memory, but don`t count
of that. But it`s allowed, that the code and the dates for that are situated
in the same section. But only in assembler you can control that correctly,
because languages like C, Pascal or similar, sections the code automatically
during the compilation. I have found up to now only one small C-code at a
bootblock, and this was a little virenkiller for KS 1.3. My respect for this
author. It`s really an outstanding achievement. The most compiler take for
help linker, which creating one part at many small parts, and so the code have
to be sectioned before. Furthermore the assembler-coder can make PC-relative
code easier.

And now we returns to the item:

You also have the facility to crunching the code, writing a little header,
which depacks the the crunched files to an executable program and runs ...

You can make, what you want, there are no limits.

An another facility are, to load directly the remaining dates from disc and
runs then the code. By that, the BootMon can`t help, because it reads only the
first two blocks from disc.

I hope, i have give you suggestions for greater code in bootblocks.

The converting file you have to be wrote to medium with @{"WriteĀBB" link "Write" 0}.

PS.: The actual bootblock will be saved into the undo-buffer and you can take
that with the function @{"UndoĀBB" link "Undo" 0}.
@endnode

