@node "BootBlock" "BootBlock"
 The BootBlock at AmigaDOS:

It consists following:

The first four bytes have the Dos-Code. But the first three bytes contain the
ASCII-Characters `DOS` ever. The fourth byte names the used filesystem. p.e.:
0 = OldFileSystem (OS1.3)
      1 = FastFileSystem (OS2.0)

After that it follows a longword, which contains the checksum of the
bootblock. If the checksum isn`t correct, so the bootblock can`t start.

The next longword points to the rootblock of the medium. You shouldn`t change
this and mostly it has the decimal value 880. Whether there are bootblocks,
especially trackloaders, at which it points to any other places. Why that can
be? I don`t know.

The next 1012 bytes are free to use for the bootcode, which are executed. The
bootcode @{fg highlight}have to be@{fg text} movable, that`s to say written in Assembler, PC-relative.
Skilled assembler-coders surely know these things. With an assembler, for
instance MaxonAss by Maxon, you can easily write your own bootblocks.

        dc.b        `DOS`,0                        ; The Doscode
        dc.l        0                        ; The checksum
        dc.l        880                        ; Pointer to RootBlock

From this point you can write your own bootCode and it have to be end with a
simple
                RTS

, otherwise the bootblocks ends never !!!


Now you can assemble your source and save the code. The code can have a
smaller size than 1024 byte, but not a longer size. Now you can read this code
in BootMon with the function `UnArch BB`, BootMon is filling empty bytes with
the value 0. For tests, you can now start the program `@{"Execute" link "Execute" 0}` and show the
result, if all it`s o.k., you can now write the code to disc. On the next boot
with this disc, that programm are started and you have written an own
bootblock.

Happy hours with BootMon wishes you the @{"Author" link "Adresse" 0}.
@endnode

@node "Adresse" "Adresse"

